The problem in your algorithm is that you are not sure if you find the exact pivot when its value is repeated.
For example for the array `[8,9,2,2,4,5,6]` your algorithm find as pivot the element in the 4th position (counting from 0 is the element 3).
In this way the left part of the array will be `[8,9,2]` which is not sorted and therefore the binary search doesn&#39;t work.

A very simply solution is to find two pivots (let&#39;s call left_pivot and right_pivot).
The right_pivot is exactly the one you are already finding and is defined as &quot;an element that has the lowest value of the array&quot;.\
The left_pivot is defined as &quot;an element that has the highest value of the array&quot; and you find with an easy modification:
```java
       while(left&lt; right){
            int mid= left+ (right- left)/ 2;
            if (mid * 2 &lt; right)
                mid = mid + 1
            // if mid&lt; right that means this much part of the array is sorted
            // then do binary search on left and mid
            if(nums[mid]&lt; nums[right])
                right= mid-1;
            // if mid&gt; right that means this part of the array is not sorted
            // then do binary search on mid+1 to right
            else
                left= mid;
        }
```

Then a binary search in the left part of the array will be done from index 0 to index left_pivot (instead of pivot-1) and the one in the right part of the array from index right_pivot to length-1

